In [4]:

tag_clusters = {}
for k in k_array:
    res = KMeans(n_clusters=k,random_state=0).fit_predict(tag_emb)
    print(res.shape)
    tag_clusters[k] = res

Now we plot the tag clusters along the 5 Principal Directions.

We plot in different graphs the result of the clustering with different $k$ clusters, and also we plot the tags projecting them on different combination of principal directions. Then we will discuss which principal directions and $k$ are the optimal in this case.

In [31]:
from bokeh.palettes import Dark2_8

for k in k_array:
    for dx in range(5):
        for dy in range(dx+1,5): 
            source = ColumnDataSource(
                data={
                    "x": tag_emb[:,dx],     # in the axis x we have the tag embedded in Principal Direction dx
                    "y": tag_emb[:,dy],     # in the axis y we have the tag embedded in Principal Direction dy
                    "name": list(tag_emb_dict.keys()),
                    "color": [Dark2_8[cluster] for cluster in tag_clusters[k]], # color deppends on the cluster
                    "cluster": tag_clusters[k] # we show the cluster number when hover
                })

            hover = HoverTool(
                tooltips=[
                    ("Name", "@name"),
                    ("Cluster","@cluster")
                ])
            tools = [hover, ResetTool(), PanTool(), WheelZoomTool(), SaveTool()]

            p = figure(plot_width=600, plot_height=260, tools=tools, title=f'Clustering with k={k}')
            p.circle("x", "y", source=source, size=7, color="color", alpha=0.5)
            p.xaxis.axis_label = f'Principal Direction {dx+1}'
            p.yaxis.axis_label = f'Principal Direction {dy+1}'

            show(p, notebook_handle=True)

After having taken a look into the graphs, we can observe that having 3 clusters ($k=3$) the Principal Direction (PD) 1 with PD 3, 4 and 5 separate quite good the clusters.

With higher values of $k$ the clusters are not so obvious and are more sparsed along the space. And with $k=2$ the clusters does not provide any new information, it is a too general clustering.

Let's see how the plots look in these cases:

We implement the jaccard distance by substracting to 1 the division of the length of the interseccion by the length of the union of both sets of movie genres.

In [12]:
def jaccard_index(a,b):
    intersection = len(set(mov_gen[a]) & set(mov_gen[b]))
    union = len(set(mov_gen[a]).union(set(mov_gen[b])))
    return 1 - (float(intersection)/float(union))

We also implement a function that will tell us if the k_medioids has converged. We know that has converged if the medioids does not change from one iteration to another.

In [14]:
def isConverged(old,act):
    if old == None:
        return False
    return old == act
In [15]:
def k_medioids(points, dist_func, k): 
    # points: we pass the movie IDs
    
    random.seed(1)
    medioids = random.sample(list(points), k)
    old_medioids=None
    clusters = [[]]
    old_clusters = None
    #after the 
    i = 0
    while isConverged(old_clusters,clusters) == False and i < 10:
        i+=1
        print(medioids)
        old_medioids = medioids.copy()
        
        old_clusters = clusters.copy()

        clusters = [[] for i in range(k)]
        for point in points:
            dist_to_medioids = []
            for medioid in medioids:
                dist_to_medioids.append(dist_func(medioid, point))
            closest_medioid = min(dist_to_medioids)
            cm_index = dist_to_medioids.index(closest_medioid)
            clusters[cm_index].append(point)
        for i in range(k):
            dists = []
            for point_x in clusters[i]:
                point_distance_sum = 0
                for point_y in clusters[i]:
                    point_distance_sum += dist_func(point_x, point_y)
                dists.append(point_distance_sum)
            min_dist_index = dists.index(min(dists))
            medioids[i] = clusters[i][min_dist_index]
    return clusters

We prepare the movies, in this case we pass the movie IDs to the function.
